<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41812942</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>25</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>25</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1879-0003</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>354</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of biological macromolecules</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Biol Macromol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Profiling carbohydrate scaffolds for &#x3b1;-amylase immobilization: A study of matrix-enzyme interaction, characterization and industrial potential of nitrocellulose-bound amylase.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>151326</StartPage><MedlinePgn>151326</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2026.151326</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0141-8130(26)01252-3</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Despite their crucial role as catalysts in carbohydrate processing, the industrial applications of amylase are often constrained by the poor stability and functional lifespan of the free enzyme. To overcome this, we explore the potential of carbohydrate-derived matrices to stabilize and enhance the performance of a haloalkali-tolerant &#x3b1;-amylase from Streptomyces roseolus strain JSo32. This research explores the functionality of the matrix material across a panel of five immobilization techniques: entrapment, physical adsorption, affinity binding, covalent binding, and ionic binding. Among the tested matrices, sodium alginate-based entrapment (2-6%) resulted in higher recovery values, ranging from 66 to 87%. The reusability of the matrix-amylase complex was evaluated over five consecutive operational cycles. Further characterization revealed a shift in the optimum temperature from 40&#xa0;&#xb0;C for the free amylase to 60&#xa0;&#xb0;C for the nitrocellulose membrane-bound amylase, accompanied by a slight decrease in the pH optimum from 10 to 9.5. FT-IR spectroscopy verified successful enzyme immobilization by revealing characteristic spectral shifts relative to the free amylase. The nitrocellulose membrane-bound amylase demonstrated detergent compatibility and effective removal of turmeric and ink stains, favoring its choice for detergent-based applications.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Teraiya</LastName><ForeName>Dhruti H</ForeName><Initials>DH</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Biosciences, Saurashtra University, Rajkot, 360005, Gujarat, India.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chauhan</LastName><ForeName>Jagruti V</ForeName><Initials>JV</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Biosciences, Saurashtra University, Rajkot, 360005, Gujarat, India.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gohel</LastName><ForeName>Sangeeta D</ForeName><Initials>SD</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Biosciences, Saurashtra University, Rajkot, 360005, Gujarat, India. Electronic address: https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&amp;user=1ahtJwYAAAAJ.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>09</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Netherlands</Country><MedlineTA>Int J Biol Macromol</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>7909578</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0141-8130</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><ChemicalList><Chemical><RegistryNumber>EC 3.2.1.1</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D00